    <h2 id="indexes">The GRO Indexes</h2>
    <p>The GRO (General Register Office), at the end of every quarter, creates an index to its latest set of birth, marriage and death registers, collectively known as the <em>GRO Index</em>. FreeBMD is an online transcription of the index, which you can search in various ways.</p>
    <p class="islet islet--light">Note: after 1983 the Index became “annual” and <em>Events</em> within them are registered by month. For example, finding <strong>01.89</strong> in the Registration field would tell you that the event (a birth, marriage or death, as appropriate) was registered in January 1989.</p>
    <p class="push-half--left push-half--bottom">A  particular event, the registration of a birth, marriage or death, for a named person, is uniquely identified in the GRO Index by quoting the: <em>who</em>, <em>what</em>, <em>when</em>, <em>where</em> and <em>which</em>:</p>
    <ul> 
      <li>the person’s name (<em>who?</em>)</li>
      <li>the event (<em>what?</em>)</li>
      <li>the quarter and year of the registration (or just the year for post-1983 indexes) (<em>when?</em>)</li>
      <li>the Registration District (known as the “District”) (<em>where?</em>)</li>
      <li>the Volume number (<em>where?</em>)</li>
      <li>the register Page number (often known as the “Page” or “Page No.”) (<em>which?</em>)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The General Register Office defines the <strong>GRO Index Reference</strong>, in their <a href="https://www.gro.gov.uk/gro/content/certificates/images/CG4.pdf" target="_blank">GRO Customer Guide No. 4 (PDF, opens in a new window)</a>, as typically consisting of: the quarter and the year, plus the Volume and the Page number — as shown on their Index pages (see Figure 1, below). This takes them to a particular page (a birth, marriage or death page) in a particular Register. The register page will have a small number of birth, marriage or death entries on it, so you need to give a name in order to identify the particular event.</p> 
  <p>Customer Guide No. 4 also refers to the District as being contained within the Volume number. (See <a href="#pageDistrictRelationship">relationships between Volume Page numbers and Districts</a> for more details).</p>
  
  <p>The GRO Indexes name the District associated with every event and GRO Online Orders confirm — the person, the event, the District; and the GRO Index Reference is confirmed as the year, quarter, Volume and Page.</p>

    <p>You can see the use of these concepts in the following extract of a marriage index page:</p>
    <figure class="site">
      <%= image_tag 'Marriage-Index-Sample.gif?sha=74d531e9b4b826cc', alt: 'Marriage Image Sample', width: 700, height: 200 %>
      <figcaption> Figure 1: part of page 214 of the Marriages Index for the March quarter of 1883</figcaption>
      </figure>
    <p> For each entry, the District name, the Volume and the (Register) Page number are on the right of the entry. Each entry is registered in a <em>District</em> (sometimes referred to as a <em>Registration District</em> or <em>RD</em> for short).</p>
  <p class="islet islet--light">Each Index page has a page number. You would not normally use that, unless you wished to reference a particular index page — or its image — or report a problem with that page. </p>

  <h3 id="pageDistrictRelationship"> Relationships between Pages and Districts</h3>
  <p> <mark>{This has been add as a result of questions raised at review - PC }</mark> </p>  
  <p> For each and every Volume, in a quarter, there will be a direct relationship between the Page numbers associated with a particular Volume and its Districts. This relationship, may “break” if either the GRO, or FreeBMD during transcription mis-record a page number, a district name or a volume number. FreeBMD carries out a number of data-base quality control checks every time it does undertakes its data-base update cycle; and this is one of the checks carried out.</p>
  <p>Events (birth, marriages and deaths) are, firstly, locally-registered in a District, in registration-date-order, onto numbered-pages of the relevant Register. Copies of pages from each District are sent on a quarterly-basis to by the GRO and are combined in a specific District-order into Volumes. Each GRO Volume has numbered-pages; and from these the Index is produced. So, a specific group of adjacent pages in a GRO Volume will directly-relate to a specific District — the entries within this group are arranged in registration-date-sequence. There will then be a discontinuity in District and dates of Registration, with the next specific group of adjacent pages in that Volume directly-relating to a diferent specific District — its entries also arranged in registration-date-sequence.</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h2 id="districts">Districts</h2>
    <p>All births, marriages and deaths in England and Wales, since the start of Civil Registration, must be registered locally in their own district. There they are recorded in <em>Registers</em>, with marriage registers having typically two or four entries per page. There are separate registers for each type of event (births, marriages and deaths) and at the end of every quarter, true copies of the pages of these registers are sent first to the Superintendent Registrar of the District.</p>
    <p>Superintendent Registrars send the pages to the GRO who use them to create the quarterly Indexes for England and Wales. These became annual indexes after the 31st December 1893, and so the date of registration of an event changed from being in a specific “quarter” to being in a specific month: for example, <strong>01.89</strong> for an event registered in January 1989.</p>
     <p>You can find out more about districts on our [Registration Districts page]("Registration Districts"). You can also visit the <a href="https://www.ukbmd.org.uk/reg/districts/index.html" target="_blank">UK BMD Registration Districts pages (opens in new tab)</a> for detailed information on which places are in each District.</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h2 id="volume">Volumes</h2>
    <p>At the GRO, all the true copies of pages received via the Superintendent Registers are sorted in registration-date order in a specific order (see <a href="#pageDistrictRelationship">relationships between Volume Page numbers and Districts</a> for more details); and grouped into <em>Volumes</em> which are assigned a Volume number — a number possibly followed by a single letter. Each of these Volumes covers a specific group of Registration Districts.</p>
  <p>The GRO changed the ordering and number of Volumes at various times; but this was generally consistent within the following periods:</p>
    
