    <p class="islet islet--light"> Note: the Volume numbers in the early indexes were identified by <em>Roman numeral</em>s and later ones by <em>Arabic numerals</em>, but FreeBMD uses only Arabic numerals for searching (so a search for Volume <em>12</em> would also find Volume <em>XII</em>).</p>
    <p>The GRO Registers themselves are held by the <a href="https://www.gro.gov.uk/" target="_blank">General Register Office (opens in new window)</a> (GRO); and under current legislation only officials of the GRO are allowed to access them. You can buy a certified copy of an entry in the Registers from the GRO: for more details, see our page on [Ordering Certificates]("Ordering Certificates").</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h2 id="page">Pages</h2>
   <p class="islet islet--neutral">Civil Registration was set up as a ‘paper-based’ system. However, parchment (not paper) was used for index pages and — as part of a security system — every page was individually numbered and was bound into an index volume or into a register (as appropriate). Loose sheets of paper could be lost and were a security risk. So, confusingly, a <em>page number</em> has two possible meanings. </p>
<p class="islet islet--neutral">If you wish to purchase a certificate, you need to quote a <strong>Page number</strong> — this is the number of the page in the GRO Register containing your record. FreeBMD transcribes pages of the GRO Indexes, so if you, for example, ask us to add a missing entry (that you see on the scan) to our database, you need to do that from the Entry Information page for the record on the <strong>Index Page</strong> immediately above the missing one. Sometimes, we need to clarify which type of page we are referring to, such as in the figure above. If we have not added a <em>clarification</em> of what we are referring to: <em>Page number </em>means <strong>Register Page number</strong>.</p>
    <p>The (Register) Page (or<strong> Page</strong>) is a number, possibly followed by a letter, that identifies the page in the Register containing the entry. You will need this page number, together with: the name of person for which you need a certificate, the <em>event,</em> when it happened, the District and the Volume, the year and quarter to uniquely identify an entry. You can use this “packet” of information, the <a href="#indexes">GRO Index Reference</a> to order a certified copy of the entry in the Register (commonly known as a “certificate”).</p>
    <p>Entries on a page are generally not related, other than having been entered in registration-date-order at the same (Registrar’s) Registration District. The exceptions being for: twins (in the birth Registers), although they might appear on adjoining pages; spouses (in the marriage registers); and possibly victims of a multiple death event (in the deaths registers), again they might appear on adjoining pages.</p>
  <p class="islet islet--neutral">The early indexes (1837 to 1851) appear to have a logical page-ordering sequence. For births, marriage and death registers: arranged by registration date and alphabetical ordering of Registration Districts within a Superintendent Registrar’s Registration District. For weddings ordering was by parish church (in alphabetical order, then Register Office weddings and Registrar-attended weddings (Non-Conformist weddings). FreeBMD does not carry out page-checks below the level of the Registration District, so this cannot be verified. After 1851, alphabetical-ordered by district can be seen in some volumes, but less so in others.</p>
  <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h2 id="qualityControl"> Database quality control checking</h2>
   <p class="islet islet--light">This section is incomplete as not some of the “functionality” is still to be implemented. Further details will be given in the next revision of this page.</p> 
  <p>FreeBMD updates its main database on an approximately 28-day cycle. During these updates, all the new entries that have been transcribed since the last update — together with any corrections made to the existing records — are incorporated into the database and made available for you to search.</p>
   
